 of indeterminacy and uncertainty. Although Bishop has recently begun to receive the critical attention she deserves, this book uniquely brings loss to the foreground in connection with identity, gender, and the fashioning of a feminist poetics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aLesbians in literature. 0aLoss (Psychology) in literature. 0aPoeticsxHistoryy20th century. 0aPoetryxPsychological aspects. 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Feminist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271076850zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271076850423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271076850.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK